title:
Optimal consumption under loss-averse multiplicative habit-formation
  preferences

sections.text:
#### Abstract

This paper studies a loss-averse version of the multiplicative habit formation preference and the corresponding optimal investment and consumption strategies over an infinite horizon. The agent's consumption preference is depicted by a general S-shaped utility function of her consumption-to-habit ratio. By considering the concave envelope of the S-shaped utility and the associated dual value function, we provide a thorough analysis of the HJB equation for the concavified problem via studying a related nonlinear free boundary problem. Based on established properties of the solution to this free boundary problem, we obtain the optimal consumption and investment policies in feedback form. Some new and technical verification arguments are developed to cope with generality of the utility function. The equivalence between the original problem and the concavified problem readily follows from the structure of the feedback controls. We also discuss some quantitative properties of the optimal policies, complemented by illustrative numerical examples and their financial implications.


Keywords: Multiplicative habit formation preference, loss aversion, S-shaped utility, HJB equation, nonlinear free-boundary problem, verification.

## 1 Introduction

In the past decades, time non-separable preferences have been popularized to explain some empirically observed phenomena such as excessive consumption smoothing ([CD89], [Sun89]) and the equity premium puzzle ([MP85], [Con90]). Among them, habit formation preference $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t}, \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$ has been widely studied to steer consumption planning, where the agent's satisfaction and risk aversion depend on the relative change of consumption rate $\mathrm{C}_{t}$ with respect to the habit level $\mathrm{H}_{t}$, rather than on the absolute consumption rate as in ([Mer69], [Mer71]). Here, the consumption habit is typically modeled by the exponentially weighted average of the past consumption that

$$
\mathrm{H}_{t}=h e^{-\rho t}+\rho \int_{0}^{t} \mathrm{e}^{-\rho(t-u)} \mathrm{C}_{u} \mathrm{~d} u, \quad t \geq 0
$$

in which $h>0$ is the initial habit and $\rho>0$ is the habit persistence parameter.
Two types of habit formation preferences can be found in the literature, namely the linear (or additive) habit formation ([Con90]) and the multiplicative habit formation ([Abe90]). The linear habit formation $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$

measures the utility based on the difference between current consumption rate and the habit. Since it is commonly assumed that $\mathrm{U}^{\prime}\left(0^{+}\right)=+\infty$, an addictive consumption constraint $\mathrm{C}_{t} \geq \mathrm{H}_{t}$ is imposed on admissible consumption policies. To sustain the control constraint without bankruptcy, the initial wealth also needs to fulfill a threshold constraint relative to the initial habit $\mathrm{W}_{0} \geq a h$ for some constant $a>0$. Along this direction, extensive studies on the characterization of the optimal consumption and some financial insights can be found in [DZ92], [EK09], [Mun08], [SS02], [Yu15], [Yu17], [YY22], [BWY24], [GHLY24], to name a few.

The multiplicative habit formation $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$, on the other hand, imposes no subsistence constraint on the agent's initial wealth. Indeed, the consumption control $\mathrm{C}_{t}$ under the multiplicative habit formation is allowed to fall below the habit formation process $\mathrm{H}_{t}$ from time to time. This non-addictive nature of multiplicative habit formation preferences has been favored by some recent studies (see [Car00b], [COW97], [COW00], [Fuh00], [CH11], [VBBL20], [LWY21], [KP22]) thanks to its flexibility in fitting diverse market environments. However, in contrast to the linear habit formation, it is generally more challenging to derive analytical characterization of the optimal consumption policies under multiplicative habit formation. In [VBBL20], the authors replaced the common habit process (1.1) with an alternative geometric specification $d \log \left(\mathrm{H}_{t}\right)=\rho\left(\log \mathrm{C}_{t}-\log \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$ and then considered the optimal lifetime consumption problem with a power-type multiplicative habit formation utility. Using the geometric specification of the habit process, they derived an approximate optimal consumption control in closed-form. To obtain the approximate control, however, they rely on a linear approximation of their budget constraint (see Section III.C therein for details) that relies on the optimal consumption-to-habit ratio to be around 1. In other words, the validity of their results rely on $\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t} \approx 1$. Using the same geometric form of the habit formation process as in [VBBL20], [KP22] further develop a duality result under power-type multiplicative habit formation utility.

The above studies rely on the Maximum Principle to analyze the underling stochastic control problems. The following studies use the Dynamic Programming Principle. [ABY22] and [ABY23] considered the common habit process (1.1) and study a new variation of multiplicative habit formation preference $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)=\frac{1}{1 \gamma}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)^{1-\gamma}$, $\gamma>1$, by mandating the additional habit constraint $\mathrm{C}_{t} \geq \alpha \mathrm{H}_{t}$ with a constant parameter $\alpha \in[0,1]$ into the set of admissible portfolio-consumption strategies. They derived the feedback form of the optimal investment and consumption policies by analyzing the corresponding Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman (HJB) equation. Due to the control constraint, however, the initial wealth therein also needs to stay above a proportion of the initial habit level (similar to previous studies on linear habit formation). Most recently, [ABG25] considered a new variation of the common habit process (1.1) with added noise, i.e. $\mathrm{dH}_{t}=\rho\left(\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t+\beta \mathrm{H}_{t} \mathrm{~d} \widetilde{\mathrm{~W}}_{t}$, in which $\widetilde{\mathrm{W}}$ is a Brownian motion independent of Brownian motion in their budget constraint. They studied an infinite horizon optimal consumption problem with multiplicative habit formation utility $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)=\frac{1}{1 \gamma}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)^{1-\gamma}$, $\gamma>1$, and established a full verification result for the underlying stochastic control problem, i.e. that the value function is the classic solution of the HJB equation. They also provided several properties of their value function, while leaving the characterization of the optimal policies for future research.

Although fruitful studies can be found in both types of habit formation preferences, neither can address loss aversion tendencies of individuals, evidently supported by empirical observations (see [KR09] and [KKP15]) that the agent might suffer more from a reduction in the relative consumption than would benefit from the same size of increment. Indeed, linear habit formation models intrinsically rule out the possibility of consumption loss relative to habit level. Albeit the multiplicative habit formation allows the agent to strategically budget the consumption plan below the habit level, the agent exhibits the same risk aversion attitude on gains and losses, failing to reflect her loss aversion in its conventional formulation.

As suggested by [KT79] and [TK92], it is more suitable to employ S-shaped two-part utility functions such that the agent's risk aversion attitudes differ when the consumption rate is above or below a reference level. In the literature of behavioral finance, the loss-averse two-part utilities with a reference point has been predominantly studied for terminal wealth optimization, see [JZ08], [HZ14], [HY19], [DZ20], [BKP21], among others. Only a handful of studies can be found that focuses on the agent's loss aversion on relative consumption towards the accustomed habit. In [Cur17], the S-shaped power utilities $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$ are considered similar to the linear habit formation preferences where, instead of the common dynamics (1.1), their habit formation process is simplified to the form of $\mathrm{H}_{t}=h+(1-\alpha) \nu h t+\alpha \mathrm{C}_{t}$ with $0 \leq \alpha<1, \nu \leq 0$ and the initial habit $h \geq 0$ such that the past consumption influence actually disappears. Later, to accommodate the conventional path-dependent habit formation process $\mathrm{H}_{t}$ in the problem $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$ under S-shaped power utilities, [VBLN20] develop the martingale duality method by taking advantage of the linear structure in terms of the consumption and imposing an artificial lower bound on the difference $\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t} \geq-\mathrm{M}$ for a fixed constant M . Recently, [LYZ24] investigate the loss-averse two-part power utilities on relative consumption $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$ based on PDE analysis where the reference process $\mathrm{H}_{t}$ is chosen as a proportion of the historical running maximum of the consumption process.

The present paper aims to pioneer the study of optimal consumption by featuring both the multiplicative habit formation and the loss-averse two-part utilities. We consider the loss-averse multiplicative habit formation $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)$ on the consumption-to-habit ratio with a reference level $\alpha>0$, namely,

$$
\mathrm{U}(c)= \begin{cases}\mathrm{U}_{+}(c-\alpha), & c>\alpha \\ -\mathrm{U} \cdot(\alpha-c), & 0 \leq c \leq \alpha\end{cases}
$$

in which $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(\cdot)$ are two general utility functions with possibly distinct risk aversion (see (2.5)). Contrary to [VBLN20] that imposes the lower bound $\mathrm{C}_{t}-\mathrm{H}_{t} \geq-\mathrm{M}$ for some $\mathrm{M}>0$ in their loss-averse linear habit formation, our formulation and methodology allow us to consider any nonnegative consumption and its aggregated habit formation process without model restrictions. Furthermore, instead of imposing a strict habit formation constraint $\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t} \geq \alpha$ considered in [ABY22], we take a more relaxed formation by assigning a loss averse utility whenever the consumption-to-habit ratio falls below the reference level $\alpha$. Thus, the constraint on the initial wealth in [ABY22] is no longer needed in our formulation, making our model applicable to agents starting at any financial situation.

It is well-known that the optimization problem is no longer concave under the above S-shaped utility. We choose to employ the concave envelope (of the utility function) and first study the HJB equation associated to the concavified stochastic control problem. To circumvent the challenge caused by the path-dependency due to habit formation, we further consider th auxiliary controls and state process, namely, the relative consumption, the relative investment, and the relative wealth, all respect to the habit formation process (see (2.7) and (2.8)). Consequently, it is sufficient to investigate an equivalent one-dimensional HJB equation under the concavified utility. Thanks to the structure of the concave envelope, it is natural to conjecture the existence of a free boundary threshold $x_{0} \geq 0$ for the relative wealth such that the optimal relative consumption is completely suspended, i.e., $c_{t}^{*}=0$, whenever the relative wealth falls below $x_{0}$; and the optimal relative consumption is characterized by the first order condition when the relative wealth diffuses above or at $x_{0}$. We eventually encounter a nonlinear free boundary problem (see problem (3.13)), and our mathematical task is to show the existence of a classical solution to this free boundary problem and establish the rigorous verification proof for the conjectured optimal controls. An added level of difficulty stems from the generality of our utility function. As noted earlier, all existing studies on multiplicative habit formation assume a restricted class of power utility

functions, namely, $\mathrm{U}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)=\frac{1}{1-\gamma}\left(\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}\right)^{1-\gamma}$ for $\gamma>1$.
The contribution of our paper is three-fold:
(i) Our work is the first study on loss-averse multiplicative habit formation that yields feedback optimal strategies. Our characterization of feedback controls leads to a straightforward numerical scheme (namely, a bisection search for the free-boundary $x_{0}$ coupled with an ODE solver) with theoretical guarantees, which allows us to discuss some interesting financial implications. Moreover, our model encompasses many existing models as limiting cases, and also allows generic utility functions; see Section 4 for detailed discussions.
(ii) We develop a methodology to analyze a type of nonlinear free boundary problem under the general S-shaped utility. In a nutshell, we choose to transform the targeted problem into several auxiliary problems, for which we are able to obtain some additional conditions and properties to assist our analysis. First, we adopt the dual transform of the original problem, leading to another nonlinear free boundary problem (see (3.16)-(3.18)). However, the dual PDE problem when the dual variable is larger than the free boundary (see (3.16)) is linear, which provides an additional explicit free boundary condition (see (3.21)) on strength of the smooth-fit principle. Next, to study the dual nonlinear free boundary problem (see (3.22)) with two free boundary conditions on the function and its derivative respectively, we propose to investigate an auxiliary system of first-order free boundary ODEs (3.23)-(3.24), whose solutions are related to the dual free boundary problem via the transformations (3.26) and (3.27) in our first main result Theorem 3.1. For this coupled system of free boundary problems, we develop some delicate arguments, new to the literature, to address the existence of the unique classical solution and to derive some important asymptotic conditions of the solutions at the boundary 0 .
(iii) Another theoretical contribution of the present paper is our verification arguments for general utility functions that satisfy mild growth conditions. Thanks to two asymptotic conditions of the solutions to the coupled system, we are able to first prove the key step of transversality condition (see Lemma 3.2) in two separate cases via different estimations and techniques. Despite the lack of an explicit structure due to the generality of the utility function and its concave envelope, we are still able to show the existence of a unique strong solution to the state SDE under the optimal feedback controls, and further verify that the solution of the HJB free boundary problem indeed coincide with the value functions of the concavified problem and the original problem.

The remainder of the paper is organized as follows. Section 2 introduces the market model and the problem formulation under the loss-averse multiplicative habit formation. Section 3 studies the HJB equation for the concavified problem and transforms it into another auxiliary free boundary problem, for which the existence of a unique classical solution is established. In addition, after obtaining some key boundary conditions of the solution, the verification theorem of the optimal feedback controls is established under general S-shaped utility functions. Section 4 presents some numerical illustrations and sensitivity analysis with respect to model parameters. Numerous financial implications, particularly the impact of habit formation and loss aversion levels, are also discussed and illustrated therein. Finally, Section 5 collects lengthy and technical proofs of the main results in the earlier sections.

# 2 Model Setup 

We consider a financial market model consisting of a riskless asset with short rate $r \geq 0$ and a risky asset whose price process $\left\{\mathrm{S}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is governed by

$$
\mathrm{dS}_{t}=(r+\mu) \mathrm{S}_{t} \mathrm{~d} t+\sigma \mathrm{S}_{t} \mathrm{dB}_{t}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

where $\mu, \sigma>0$ are the expected excess rate of return and volatility of the risky asset, and $\mathrm{B}=\left\{\mathrm{B}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is a standard Brownian motion supported on the filtered probability space $\left(\Omega, \mathcal{F}, \mathbb{F}=\left\{\mathcal{F}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}, \mathbb{P}\right)$ with $\mathbb{F}$ being the augmented filtration of B .

An individual (henceforth, the agent) funds her lifetime consumption by investing in this market. Let $\Pi_{t}$ stand for the amount of wealth invested in the risky asset and $\mathrm{C}_{t}$ be the consumption rate at time $t$. The agent's self-financing wealth process $\left\{\mathrm{W}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ then satisfies

$$
\mathrm{dW}_{t}=\left(r \mathrm{~W}_{t}+\mu \Pi_{t}-\mathrm{C}_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t+\sigma \Pi_{t} \mathrm{dB}_{t}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

with the initial wealth $\mathrm{W}_{0}=w>0$.
Definition 2.1. Given $w>0$, a progressively measurable process $(\Pi, \mathrm{C})=\left\{\left(\Pi_{t}, \mathrm{C}_{t}\right)\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is an admissible investment and consumption control pair if $\int_{0}^{t}\left(\left|\mathrm{C}_{u}\right|+\Pi_{u}^{2}\right) \mathrm{d} u<+\infty$ and $\mathrm{W}_{t} \geq 0$ for all $t \geq 0$, in which $\left\{\mathrm{W}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is the strong solution of (2.2). $\mathcal{A}_{0}(w)$ denotes the set of all admissible controls starting with the initial wealth $w$.

In our model, it is assumed that the agent gradually develops consumption habits such that her performance and risk aversion on consumption depend on the relative changes with respect to her accustomed habit level. In particular, her habit formation process $\left\{\mathrm{H}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$, also called the standard of living process, is conventionally defined as the exponentially-weighted average of the past consumption up to date, namely

$$
\mathrm{H}_{t}:=h+\rho \int_{0}^{t}\left(\mathrm{C}_{u}-\mathrm{H}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u=h e^{-\rho t}+\rho \int_{0}^{t} \mathrm{e}^{-\rho(t-u)} \mathrm{C}_{u} \mathrm{~d} u, \quad t \geq 0
$$

in which $h>0$ is the initial habit level and $\rho>0$ stands for the persistence rate of the past consumption levels. A larger value of $\rho$ indicates that the agent's habit is more inclined to recent consumption behavior compared to past consumption rates in distant time.

In contrast to previous studies in the literature, we aim to study the loss averse version of the multiplicative habit formation preference to account for the agent's psychological difference towards the same sized gain and loss of relative consumption with reference to the habit formation process. To this end, we adapt a general S-shaped two-part utility (see [KT79] and [TK92]) to encode the agent's loss aversion in the multiplicative habit formation, namely,

$$
\mathrm{U}(c)= \begin{cases}\mathrm{U}_{+}(c-\alpha), & c>\alpha \\ -\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha-c), & 0 \leq c \leq \alpha\end{cases}
$$

Here, $0<\alpha \leq 1$ is the reference point for the agent's consumption-to-habit ratio, indicating the scenario of the relative consumption $0 \leq \mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}<\alpha$ as loss, and the scenario $\mathrm{C}_{t} / \mathrm{H}_{t}>\alpha$ as gain. Distinct risk aversion stemming from utilities $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(\cdot)$ then effectively depict the agent's different feelings over same-sized gains and losses in the relative consumption rates. That is, $c \mapsto-\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha-c)$ is the (convex) loss-averse utility function in

the loss region $0 \leq c \leq \alpha$, and $c \mapsto \mathrm{U}_{+}(c-\alpha)$ is the (concave) risk-averse utility function in the gain region $c>\alpha$. In (2.4), it is assumed that $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(\cdot)$ are concave utility functions satisfying

$$
\mathrm{U}_{ \pm} \in \mathcal{U}:=\left\{f \in \mathcal{C}^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}_{+}\right): f^{\prime}>0, f^{\prime \prime}<0, f^{\prime}(+\infty)=0, f(0)=0\right\}
$$

Note that $\mathrm{U}(\alpha)=\mathrm{U}_{+}(0)=-\mathrm{U}_{-}(0)=0$ since $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(0)=0$ by (2.5). This assumption is taken without loss of generality, as we can always shift a utility function by a constant.

Later, in Subsection 3.1, we will impose two additional assumptions on the utility function U, namely, Assumptions 3.1 and 3.2 below. These assumptions are technical in nature, but, they are common in the literature. See Remarks 3.1 and 3.2 for further discussion.

To find her optimal investment and consumption policies, the agent needs to solve the following stochastic control problem

$$
\mathrm{V}_{0}(w, h)=\sup _{(\Pi, \mathrm{C}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0}(w)} \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{+\infty} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta t} \mathrm{U}\left(\frac{\mathrm{C}_{t}}{\mathrm{H}_{t}}\right) \mathrm{d} t\right], \quad w, h>0
$$

in which $\delta>0$ is her discount rate for utility of consumption. This stochastic control problem has two state processes, namely $\left\{\mathrm{W}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ and $\left\{\mathrm{H}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$. Next, we reduce the number of state processes to one by considering an equivalent form of (2.6).

Fix the values of $w, h>0$ and consider an arbitrary admissible policy $(\Pi, \mathrm{C}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0}(w)$. Let $\left\{\mathrm{W}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ and $\left\{\mathrm{H}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ be the corresponding wealth and habit processes given by (2.2) and (2.3), respectively. Note that, by (2.3), $\mathrm{H}_{t} \geq h \mathrm{e}^{-\rho t}>0$. Thus, we can define the relative wealth process $\left\{\mathrm{X}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$, the relative investment process $\left\{\pi_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$, and the relative consumption process $\left\{c_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$, respectively, by

$$
\mathrm{X}_{t}:=\frac{\mathrm{W}_{t}}{\mathrm{H}_{t}}, \quad \pi_{t}:=\frac{\Pi_{t}}{\mathrm{H}_{t}}, \quad c_{t}:=\frac{\mathrm{C}_{t}}{\mathrm{H}_{t}}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

Combining Itô's formula, (2.2), and (2.3), we can write the dynamics of X as

$$
\mathrm{dX}_{t}=\left((r+\rho) \mathrm{X}_{t}+\mu \pi_{t}-\left(1+\rho \mathrm{X}_{t}\right) c_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t+\sigma \pi_{t} \mathrm{~dB}_{t}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

with $\mathrm{X}_{0}=x:=w / h>0$. With these observations in mind, we define the set of admissible relative consumption and investment controls as follows.

Definition 2.2. Given $x>0$, a progressively measurable process $(\pi, c)=\left\{\left(\pi_{t}, c_{t}\right)\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is an admissible relative investment and consumption policy if $\int_{0}^{t}\left(\left|c_{u}\right|+\pi_{u}^{2}\right) \mathrm{d} u<+\infty$ and $\mathrm{X}_{t} \geq 0$ for all $t \geq 0$, in which $\left\{\mathrm{X}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is the strong solution of (2.8). We denote by $\mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(x)$ the set of all admissible relative investment and consumption policies starting with relative wealth $x$.

As the next result shows, for any $h, w>0$, the sets $\mathcal{A}_{0}(w)$ and $\mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(w / h)$ are equivalent in the sense that each admissible investment and consumption policy $(\Pi, \mathrm{C}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0}(w)$ corresponds to an admissible relative investment and consumption policy $(\pi, c) \in \mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(w / h)$, and vice versa. We omit its proof, which is a straightforward application of Itô's formula.

Lemma 2.1. Assume that $w, h>0$. For any $(\Pi, \mathrm{C}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0}(w)$, we have $(\Pi / \mathrm{H}, \mathrm{C} / \mathrm{H}) \in \mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(w / h)$. Conversely, if $(\pi, c) \in \mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(h / w)$, then $(\pi \mathrm{W} / \mathrm{X}, c \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{X}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0}(w)$ in which the relative wealth $\left\{\mathrm{X}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is given by (2.8) and the wealth process $\left\{\mathrm{W}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is given by

$$
\frac{\mathrm{dW}_{t}}{\mathrm{~W}_{t}}=\left(r+\mu \frac{\pi_{t}}{\mathrm{X}_{t}}-\frac{c_{t}}{\mathrm{X}_{t}}\right) \mathrm{d} t+\sigma \frac{\pi_{t}}{\mathrm{X}_{t}} \mathrm{~dB}_{t}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

with $\mathrm{W}_{0}=w$.

From Lemma 2.1, it follows that (2.6) is equivalent to the following one-dimensional stochastic control problem

$$
\mathrm{V}(x)=\sup _{(\pi, c) \in A_{\text {rel. }}(x)} \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{+\infty} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta t} \mathrm{U}\left(c_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t\right], \quad x>0
$$

in which the only state variable is the wealth-to-habit ratio $\left\{\mathrm{X}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$. Once we solved (2.9), we can use Lemma 2.1 to obtain the optimal investment and consumption polices and the corresponding optimal wealth.

Remark 2.1. In light of Lemma 2.1 and by (2.6) and (2.9), it follows that $\mathrm{V}_{0}(w, h)=\mathrm{V}(w / h)$ for $w, h>0$. That is, our dimension reduction notably does not rely on a specific form of the utility functions $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(c)$. In particular, (2.6) and (2.9) are equivalent even if the utility functions $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(c)$ in (2.4) are not standard power, log, or exponential utilities.

# 3 Methodology and Main Results 

Our goal in this section is to solve the stochastic control problem (2.9) under the general S-shaped multiplicative habit formation preference and to obtain the optimal relative investment and consumption policies in feedback form. To this end, we follow a three-step procedure described below:
Step-1: We first consider the concavified version of (2.9) by replacing the utility function $\mathrm{U}(c)$ with its concave envelope $\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)$, see (3.1) below. We write down the Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman (HJB) equation for the concavified problem, and transform it to a free-boundary problem (3.13) based on the conjectured optimal consumption control in (3.9). The arguments in this step are mainly motivational. Rigorous arguments are postponed to Steps 2 and 3.
Step-2: We solve the free-boundary problem and obtain a candidate value function $v(x)$ for the concavified problem (see corollary 3.2). Along the way, we also establish several important properties of $v(x)$ and verify the conjectures in Step-1.
Step-3: Based on the obtained properties of $v(x)$, we verify the optimality of the feedback controls and show that the solution $v(x)$ to the HJB equation coincides with both the value function $\widetilde{\mathrm{V}}(x)$ of the concavified problem (3.1) and the value function $\mathrm{V}(x)$ of the original problem (2.9).

### 3.1 Step-1: The concavified problem and its HJB equation

To study the non-concave stochastic control problem (2.9) under the S-shaped utility, we follow the routine by considering its concavified formulation (see [Car00a]), namely,

$$
\widetilde{\mathrm{V}}(x)=\sup _{(c, \pi) \in A_{\text {rel. }}(x)} \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{+\infty} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta t} \widetilde{\mathrm{U}}\left(c_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t\right], \quad x>0
$$

where $\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}$ is the concave envelope of the S-shaped utility $\mathrm{U}(c)$ in (2.4), that is,

$$
\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c):=\sup _{s, t}\left\{\frac{(t-c) \mathrm{U}(t)+(c-s) \mathrm{U}(s)}{t-s}: 0 \leq s \leq c \leq t\right\}, \quad c \geq 0
$$

To this end, some growth conditions on the S-shaped utility are necessarily needed. In fact, Figure 1 illustrates two possible choices of the utility function $\mathrm{U}(c)$ along with their concave envelopes $\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)$ given by (3.2). It is worth noting here that, unlike most of the literature on loss-averse preferences, the general S-shaped

utility allows for the loss-averse and the risk-averse parts of the utility to be of different classes. For example, in (2.4), we may choose a power utility $\mathrm{U}_{+}(c)=\frac{(c+\epsilon)^{p}}{p}-\frac{\epsilon^{p}}{p}$ for the risk-averse part, and an exponential utility $\mathrm{U}_{-}(c)=1-\mathrm{e}^{-q c}$ (or a log-utility $\mathrm{U}_{-}(c)=\log ((c+q) / q)$ ) for the loss-averse part, with $\epsilon>0, p<1$, and $q>0$. Furthermore, we allow for the S-shaped utility to be non-differentiable at the loss reference point (i.e. $\mathrm{U}^{\prime}\left(\alpha^{-}\right) \neq \mathrm{U}^{\prime}\left(\alpha^{+}\right)$), as in the case of the left plot in Figure 1.

Figure 1: Plots of two possible S-shaped utility functions $\mathrm{U}(c)$ (the solid curves) and their concave envelopes $\widehat{\mathrm{U}}(c)$ (the dashed curves), where we have set $\alpha=0.75$. Note that $\mathrm{U}(c)$ and $\widehat{\mathrm{U}}(c)$ coincide on $\left[c_{0},+\infty\right)$, and that $\widehat{\mathrm{U}}$ is linear on $\left[0, c_{0}\right]$. The constant $c_{0}$ is defined in Lemma 3.1 in Section 3, and is the unique solution of $c_{0} \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)-\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)=\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha)$. Note, also, that the loss and gain utility functions $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}$in (2.5) can be different, and the S-shaped utility $\mathrm{U}(c)$ can be non-differentiable at the reference point $\alpha$ (as in the right plot).

We impose two conditions on the general utility function $\mathrm{U}(c)$, which will be used later to obtain and verify the optimal controls. The first assumption guarantees that $\mathrm{U}(c)$ has a smooth concave envelope; see Lemma 3.1 below.

Assumption 3.1. The utility functions $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(c)$ in (2.4) satisfy $\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha) \leq \alpha \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}(0)$.
Remark 3.1. Assumption 3.1 is satisfied by the S-shaped utility functions commonly used in the literature, on which one of the following assumptions is typically imposed:

- $\mathrm{U}^{\prime}\left(\alpha^{+}\right)=\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(0^{+}\right)=+\infty$, such as two-part power utilities (see (4.1)); or,
- $\mathrm{U}(c)$ is differentiable at the reference point $\alpha$, that is, $\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}(0)=\mathrm{U}_{-}^{\prime}(0)$.

Indeed, Assumption 3.1 trivially holds under the first condition, while under the second condition, Assumption 3.1 also holds because, by the concavity of $\mathrm{U}_{-}(c)$, we have $\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha) \leq \alpha \mathrm{U}_{-}^{\prime}(0)=\alpha \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}(0)$.

Our second assumption on the S-shaped utility function $\mathrm{U}(c)$ is a growth condition on the gain utility $\mathrm{U}_{+}(c)$ as $c \rightarrow+\infty$. This assumption is needed to facilitate the proof of the transversality condition for the stochastic control problem (2.9), see Lemma 3.2 in Subsection 3.3.

Assumption 3.2. There exist constants $a_{1}, a_{2}, a_{3}>0$, and $a_{4} \geq 0$ such that the gain utility function $\mathrm{U}_{+}(\cdot)$ in (2.4) satisfies the growth condition $\mathrm{U}_{+}(x) \leq a_{1}+x \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}(x)+a_{2} \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}(x)^{-a_{4}}$ for all $x>a_{3}$.

Remark 3.2. It is straightforward to check that Assumption 3.2 holds for the power, log, and Symmetric Asymptotic Hyperbolic Absolute Risk Aversion (SAHARA) utility functions (see (4.7)), as well as any upper bounded utility function such as the exponential utility. In particular, note that we allow for the full range of power utilities, i.e. $\mathrm{U}(x)=x^{1-\gamma} /(1-\gamma)$ for $\gamma>0$. As pointed out in the introduction, existing results on multiplicative habit formation only consider power utilities for $\gamma>1$.

We expect that problems (2.9) and (3.1) are equivalent in the sense that $\mathrm{V}(x)=\widetilde{\mathrm{V}}(x)$ for $x>0$, and that they share a common optimal control $\left(c^{*}, \pi^{*}\right)$. These results will be proved in Theorem 3.2 in Subsection 3.3 below.

The Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman (HJB) equation corresponding to (3.1) is

$$
\sup _{\pi \in \mathbb{R}, c \geq 0}\left\{-\delta v(x)+((r+\rho) x+\mu \pi-(1+\rho x) c) v^{\prime}(x)+\frac{1}{2} \sigma^{2} \pi^{2} v^{\prime \prime}(x)+\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)\right\}=0
$$

for $x>0$. Taking the ansatz $v^{\prime \prime}(x)<0$ for the solution of (3.3), we have the maximizer

$$
\pi^{*}(x):=\underset{\pi \in \mathbb{R}}{\arg \max }\left\{\frac{1}{2} \sigma^{2} \pi^{2} v^{\prime \prime}(x)+\mu \pi v^{\prime}(x)\right\}=-\frac{\mu}{\sigma^{2}} \frac{v^{\prime}(x)}{v^{\prime \prime}(x)}
$$

The HJB equation (3.3) then becomes

$$
\sup _{c \geq 0}\left\{\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)-c(1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right\}-\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} \frac{v^{\prime}(x)^{2}}{v^{\prime \prime}(x)}+(r+\rho) x v^{\prime}(x)-\delta v(x)=0, \quad x \geq 0
$$

We use the next lemma to evaluate the term involving the maximization over $c$. The lemma relies on Assumption 3.1 above. Its proof is straightforward and thus omitted.

Lemma 3.1. Consider the $S$-shaped utility $\mathrm{U}(c)$ in (2.4) with $\alpha>0$ and $\mathrm{U}_{ \pm}(c)$ satisfying (2.5) and Assumption 3.1. The concave envelope $\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)$ in (3.2) is given by

$$
\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)= \begin{cases}-\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha)+\phi_{0} c, & 0 \leq c \leq c_{0} \\ \mathrm{U}(c)=\mathrm{U}_{+}(c-\alpha), & c>c_{0}\end{cases}
$$

in which $\phi_{0}:=\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)$ and $c_{0} \geq \alpha$ is the unique solution of $c_{0} \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)-\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)=\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha)$. Furthermore, for any $\phi>0, \tilde{c}(\phi)$ given by

$$
\tilde{c}(\phi):= \begin{cases}0, & \phi>\phi_{0} \\ \alpha+\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}(\phi), & 0<\phi \leq \phi_{0}\end{cases}
$$

is a common maximizer for both problems $\max _{c \geq 0}\{\mathrm{U}(c)-\phi c\}$ and $\max _{c \geq 0}\{\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)-\phi c\}$.
With (3.7) in mind, we speculate that there exists a (yet to be determined) constant $x_{0} \geq 0$ such that $v(x)$ (i.e. the solution of (3.5)) satisfies

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
(1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)>\phi_{0}, \quad 0 \leq x<x_{0} \\
\left(1+\rho x_{0}\right) v^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)=\phi_{0} \\
0<(1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)<\phi_{0}, \quad x>x_{0}
\end{array}\right.
$$

for the constant $\phi_{0}$ given in Lemma 3.1. These conjectured inequalities will be verified later in Corollary 3.2 in Subsection 3.2. Setting $\phi=(1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)$ in (3.7) and using (3.8), we readily get that

$$
\sup _{c \geq 0}\left\{\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(c)-c(1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right\}= \begin{cases}\widetilde{\mathrm{U}}(0)=\mathrm{U}(0), & 0 \leq x<x_{0} \\ \mathrm{G}\left((1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right), & x \geq x_{0}\end{cases}
$$

where we define

$$
\mathrm{G}(\phi):=\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(\phi)\right)-\phi\left(\alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(\phi)\right), \quad 0<\phi \leq \phi_{0}
$$

For future reference, we also note that the maximizer of $c$ in (3.9) is given by

$$
c^{*}(x):= \begin{cases}0, & 0 \leq x<x_{0} \\ \alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left((1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right), & x \geq x_{0}\end{cases}
$$

Remark 3.3. Note that the maximizer $c^{*}(x)$ in (3.11) has a jump at $x=x_{0}$ because $\lim _{x \rightarrow x_{0}^{-}} c^{*}(x)=0$, but

$$
c^{*}\left(x_{0}\right)=\alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\left(1+\rho x_{0}\right) v^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)\right)=\alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\phi_{0}\right)=c_{0} \geq \alpha>0
$$

Here, we have used (3.8) and that $\phi_{0}:=\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)$ with the constant $c_{0}$ in Lemma 3.1. Note also that there is no discontinuity in the optimal value given by (3.9) at $x=x_{0}$. This can be confirmed as follows. By (3.8) and (3.10), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{G}\left(\left(1+\rho x_{0}\right) v^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)\right) & =\mathrm{G}\left(\phi_{0}\right)=\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\phi_{0}\right)\right)-\phi_{0}\left(\alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\phi_{0}\right)\right) \\
& =\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)-\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right) c_{0}=-\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha)=\mathrm{U}(0)
\end{aligned}
$$

in which the second-to-last step follows from $c_{0} \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)-\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)=\mathrm{U}_{-}(\alpha)$ (which holds by the definition of $c_{0}$ in Lemma 3.1), and the last step follows from (3.6).

By using (3.9), the HJB equation (3.5) becomes the following free-boundary problem for the function $v(x)$ and with the free boundary $x_{0} \geq 0$,

$$
\begin{cases}\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} \frac{v^{\prime}(x)^{2}}{v^{\prime \prime}(x)}+(r+\rho) x v^{\prime}(x)-\delta v(x)+\mathrm{U}(0)=0, & 0 \leq x<x_{0} \\ -\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} \frac{v^{\prime}(x)^{2}}{v^{\prime \prime}(x)}+\mathrm{G}\left((1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right)+(r+\rho) x v^{\prime}(x)-\delta v(x)=0, & x \geq x_{0} \\ \left(1+\rho x_{0}\right) v^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)=\phi_{0} \\ \lim _{x \rightarrow 0^{+}} \frac{v^{\prime}(x)}{v^{\prime \prime}(x)}=0, & \end{cases}
$$

in which $\mathrm{G}(\phi)$ is given by (3.10) and $\phi_{0}$ is defined in Lemma 3.1. In (3.13), the free boundary conditions at $x=x_{0}$ follows from (3.8). Furthermore, in light of (3.4), the initial condition at $x \rightarrow 0^{+}$means that once the wealth hits zero, it is optimal not to invest in the risky asset (in fact, this is the only admissible investment policy at $x=0$ ).

By reversing the argument leading to (3.13), it follows that if a solution $\left(v(x), x_{0}\right)$ of the free-boundary problem (3.13) satisfies (3.8) and $v^{\prime \prime}(x)<0$ for $x>0$, then $v(x)$ is a solution of the HJB equation (3.5). In the next subsection, we establish the existence of a solution $\left(v(x), x_{0}\right)$ to this free boundary problem, see Corollary 3.2 .

# 3.2 Step-2: Auxiliary nonlinear free boundary problems 

To study problem (3.13), we first consider the Legendre transform

$$
u(y):=\sup _{x>0}\{v(x)-x y\}, y>0
$$

which implies the following relationships between $v(x)$ and $u(y)$

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
v\left(\left(v^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(y)\right)=u(y)-y u^{\prime}(y) \\
\left(v^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(y)=-u^{\prime}(y) \\
v^{\prime \prime}\left(\left(v^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(y)\right)=-1 / u^{\prime \prime}(y)
\end{array}\right.
$$

By applying the change of variable $y=v^{\prime}(x) \Leftrightarrow x=\left(v^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(y)$ and using (3.15), we can rewrite the nonlinear free-boundary problem (3.13) for $x \geq 0$ as the dual nonlinear free-boundary problem for $u(y)$ for $y>0$ with the free boundary $y_{0}=v^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)>0$,

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} y^{2} u^{\prime \prime}(y)+(\delta-r-\rho) y u^{\prime}(y)-\delta u(y)+\mathrm{U}(0)=0, & y>y_{0} \\
\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} y^{2} u^{\prime \prime}(y)+\mathrm{G}\left(y-\rho y u^{\prime}(y)\right)+(\delta-r-\rho) y u^{\prime}(y)-\delta u(y)=0, & 0<y \leq y_{0} \\
y_{0}-\rho y_{0} u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)=\phi_{0},
\end{array}
$$

and

$$
\lim _{y \rightarrow+\infty} u^{\prime}(y)=\lim _{y \rightarrow+\infty} y u^{\prime \prime}(y)=0
$$

One advantage of working with the dual problem (3.16)-(3.18) (instead of the original nonlinear free boundary problem (3.13)) lies in the fact that (3.16) is a linear Euler equation, which admits a general solution given by the explicit form

$$
u(y)=\mathrm{A}_{1} y^{\lambda}+\mathrm{A}_{2} y^{\lambda^{\prime}}+\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta}, \quad y>y_{0}
$$

in which $\mathrm{A}_{1}$ and $\mathrm{A}_{2}$ are constants to be determined,

$$
\lambda:=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left(\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}}+r+\rho-\delta-\sqrt{\left(\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}}+r+\rho-\delta\right)^{2}+2 \delta \frac{\mu^{2}}{\sigma^{2}}}\right) \in\left(-\frac{2 \delta \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}, 0\right)
$$

and

$$
\lambda^{\prime}:=\frac{2 \delta \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2} \lambda}>1
$$

Remark 3.4. That

$$
-\frac{2 \delta \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}<\lambda<0, \quad \text { and } \quad \lambda^{\prime}>1
$$

are shown as follows. Note that $\lambda$ and $\lambda^{\prime}$ are, respectively, the positive and the negative roots of the quadratic equation $f(x):=\mu^{2} x^{2} /\left(2 \sigma^{2}\right)-\left(\mu^{2} /\left(2 \sigma^{2}\right)+r+\rho-\delta\right) x-\delta=0$. As $f\left(-2 \delta \sigma^{2} / \mu^{2}\right)=2(r+\rho) \delta \sigma^{2} / \mu^{2}>0$ and $f(0)=-\delta<0$, it follows that $-2 \delta \sigma^{2} / \mu^{2}<\lambda<0$ which, in turn, yields that $\lambda^{\prime}:=-2 \delta \sigma^{2} /\left(\mu^{2} \lambda\right)>1$.

Differentiating (3.19) yields $u^{\prime}(y)=\lambda \mathrm{A}_{1} y^{\lambda-1}+\lambda^{\prime} \mathrm{A}_{2} y^{\lambda^{\prime}-1}$ and $y u^{\prime \prime}(y)=\lambda(\lambda-1) \mathrm{A}_{1} y^{\lambda-1}+\lambda^{\prime}\left(\lambda^{\prime}-1\right) \mathrm{A}_{2} y^{\lambda^{\prime}-1}$, for $y>y_{0}$. In light of (3.20), the boundary condition (3.18) holds only if $\mathrm{A}_{2}=0$. From (3.17), we then obtain the value of $\mathrm{A}_{1}$. That is,

$$
\phi_{0}=y_{0}-\rho y_{0} u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)=y_{0}-\rho y_{0} \lambda \mathrm{~A}_{1} y_{0}^{\lambda-1} \quad \Longrightarrow \quad \mathrm{~A}_{1}=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho \lambda y_{0}^{\lambda}}
$$

Substituting $\mathrm{A}_{1}$ and $\mathrm{A}_{2}$ back into (3.19) yields

$$
u(y)=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho \lambda}\left(\frac{y}{y_{0}}\right)^{\lambda}+\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta}, \quad y>y_{0}
$$

Thus, by the smooth-fit principle, we can reduce the free-boundary problem (3.16)-(3.18) to the following free-boundary problem only for $0<y \leq y_{0}$ with the free boundary $y_{0}>0$,

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} y^{2} u^{\prime \prime}(y)+\mathrm{G}\left(y-\rho y u^{\prime}(y)\right)+(\delta-r-\rho) y u^{\prime}(y)-\delta u(y)=0, \quad 0<y \leq y_{0} \\
y_{0}-\rho y_{0} u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)=\phi_{0} \\
u\left(y_{0}\right)=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho \lambda}+\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta}
\end{array}\right.
$$

In particular, the additional explicit free boundary condition $u\left(y_{0}\right)=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho \lambda}+\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta}$ will play an important role in showing the existence of the classical solution to (3.22). Once this free-boundary problem is solved, we in turn obtain a solution of the free-boundary problem (3.16)-(3.18) by pasting the solution in (3.21).

The following theorem is our first main result of this section. It addresses the solution of the nonlinear free-boundary problem (3.22) by considering another auxiliary system of first-order free boundary problems. In particular, we first introduce the auxiliary functions $\varphi(y)$ and $\psi(y)$ as the solution of (3.23), for which we establish several important properties that will be further used in future verification arguments. Its proof is technical and lengthy, which is postponed to Subsections 5.1 and 5.2.

Theorem 3.1. (i) There exists a constant $y_{0} \in\left(\frac{\phi_{0} \lambda}{\lambda-1}, \phi_{0}\right)$, an increasing function $\varphi:\left(0, y_{0}\right] \rightarrow\left(0, \phi_{0}\right)$, and a function $\psi:\left(0, y_{0}\right] \rightarrow(0,1)$ satisfying the coupled system of first-order free boundary ODEs

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\varphi^{\prime}(y)=\frac{1}{y} \varphi(y)(1-\psi(y)) \\
\psi^{\prime}(y)=-\frac{2 \rho \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left[\frac{1-\psi(y)}{y}\left(\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \psi(y)-\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}(\varphi(y))+\frac{r-\delta}{\rho}+1-\alpha\right)-\frac{r+\rho}{\rho \varphi(y)}+\frac{\delta}{\rho y}\right]
\end{array}\right.
$$

for $0<y \leq y_{0}$ with the free boundary conditions

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\varphi\left(y_{0}\right)=\phi_{0} \\
\psi\left(y_{0}\right)=\frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\phi_{0} \mu^{2}}\left(\frac{\delta}{\lambda}+r+\rho-\delta\right)\left(y_{0}-\phi_{0}\right)
\end{array}\right.
$$

Moreover, at least one of these equations holds: $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \varphi(y)>0$ or $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \psi(y)=1$.
(ii) Given the solution $\left(\varphi(y), \psi(y), y_{0}\right)$ in part $(i)$, let us define

$$
u(y):=\frac{1}{\delta}\left[\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \varphi(y) \psi(y)+\mathrm{G}(\varphi(y))+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}(y-\varphi(y))\right], \quad 0<y \leq y_{0}
$$

It then holds that $\left(u(y), y_{0}\right)$ is a solution of the free-boundary problem (3.22). Furthermore, we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& u^{\prime}(y)=\frac{y-\varphi(y)}{\rho y}, \quad 0<y<y_{0} \\
& u^{\prime \prime}(y)=\frac{1}{\rho y^{2}} \varphi(y) \psi(y), \quad 0<y<y_{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

$u(y)$ is decreasing and convex on $\left(0, y_{0}\right)$, and $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} u^{\prime}(y)=-\infty$.
Proof. See Subsections 5.1 and 5.2 .
As a result, we obtain the solution of the free-boundary problem (3.16)-(3.18).
Corollary 3.1. Let $y_{0}$ be the constant in Theorem 3.1.(i), and assume that $u:(0, \infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is given by (3.21) and (3.25). Then, $\left(u(y), y_{0}\right)$ solves the free boundary problem (3.16)-(3.18). Furthermore, $u \in \mathrm{C}^{2}(0, \infty)$ is strictly decreasing and strictly convex, $u^{\prime}\left(0^{+}\right)=-\infty$, and $u^{\prime}(+\infty)=0$.

Proof. These statements are direct consequences of Theorem 3.1 and the explicit expression (3.21).
As a second corollary of Theorem 3.1, we can now solve the original free-boundary problem (3.13) for $\left(v(x), x_{0}\right)$ by the inverting the Legendre transform (3.14).

Corollary 3.2. Let $\left(u(y), y_{0}\right)$ be the solution of the free boundary problem (3.16)-(3.18) in Corollary 3.1. Then, $\left(v(x), x_{0}\right)$ given by

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
v(x):=u\left(\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x)\right)+x\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x), \quad x>0 \\
x_{0}:=\frac{\phi_{0}-y_{0}}{\rho y_{0}}
\end{array}\right.
$$

satisfy (3.13), (3.8), $v^{\prime}(+\infty)=0, v^{\prime}\left(0^{+}\right)=+\infty, v^{\prime}(x)=\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x)>0$, and $v^{\prime \prime}(x)=-1 / u^{\prime \prime}\left(v^{\prime}(x)\right)<0$ for $x>0$.

Proof. For ease of notation, let us define $\mathrm{J}:(-\infty, 0) \rightarrow(0, \infty)$ by $\mathrm{J}:=\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}$. We derive from (3.28) and the chain rule that $v^{\prime}(x)=\mathrm{J}(-x)>0$ and $v^{\prime \prime}(x)=-1 / u^{\prime \prime}(\mathrm{J}(-x))<0$ for $x>0$, in which the inequalities hold thanks to the fact that $u(y)$ is strictly decreasing and convex by Corollary 3.1. That $v^{\prime}(+\infty)=0$ and $v^{\prime}\left(0^{+}\right)=+\infty$ follows from $u^{\prime}\left(0^{+}\right)=-\infty$ and $u^{\prime}(+\infty)=0$ shown in Corollary 3.1. By (3.26), $x_{0}:=\frac{\phi_{0}-y_{0}}{\rho y_{0}}=-u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)$. Therefore, by (3.15) and the correspondence $y=v^{\prime}(x)=\mathrm{J}(-x) \Leftrightarrow x=-u^{\prime}(y)$, we conclude that $v(x)$ and $x_{0}$ (given by (3.28)) satisfy (3.13). To verify (3.8), we note that

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} x}\left((1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right)=\rho v^{\prime}(x)+(1+\rho x) v^{\prime \prime}(x)=\rho y-\frac{1-\rho u^{\prime}(y)}{u^{\prime \prime}(y)}=\rho y\left(1-\frac{1}{\psi(y)}\right)<0
$$

for $0<y<y_{0}$ (equivalently, $x>x_{0}$ ). Here, we have used (3.26) and (3.27). Moreover, we have $u^{\prime}(y)=$ $\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho} \frac{y^{\lambda-1}}{y_{0}^{\lambda}}$ and $u^{\prime \prime}(y)=\frac{\left(y_{0}-\phi_{0}\right)(\lambda-1)}{\rho} \frac{y^{\lambda-2}}{y_{0}^{\lambda}}$, for $y>y_{0}$. Therefore,

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} x}\left((1+\rho x) v^{\prime}(x)\right)=\rho v^{\prime}(x)+(1+\rho x) v^{\prime \prime}(x)=\rho y-\frac{1-\rho u^{\prime}(y)}{u^{\prime \prime}(y)}=\lambda \rho y-\frac{1}{u^{\prime \prime}(y)}<0
$$

In view of $\left(1+\rho x_{0}\right) v^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right)=\phi_{0}$, (3.8) readily follows.

# 3.3 Step-3: The verification theorem and the optimal feedback controls 

In this subsection, our goal is to establish the verification theorem that provides the optimal investment and consumption policies in feedback form and in terms of the solution $\left(\varphi(y), \psi(y), y_{0}\right)$ of the auxiliary system of first-order free boundary problems (3.23)-(3.24).

We need the next result regarding $v(x)$ (of Corollary 3.2), which is the so-called transversality condition. Its proof, included in Subsection 5.3, relies on Assumption 3.2 as well as various properties of the solution $\left(\varphi(y), \psi(y), y_{0}\right)$ of (3.23)-(3.24) that was established by Theorem 3.1.

Lemma 3.2. Suppose that the utility function $\mathrm{U}(\cdot)$ satisfies (2.4), (2.5), Assumption 3.1, and Assumption 3.2. Then, the function $v(\cdot)$ of (3.28) fulfills the transversality condition

$$
\lim _{\mathrm{T} \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{E}\left[e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} v\left(\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right]=0
$$

for all $\left(\pi_{t}, c_{t}\right)_{t \geq 0} \in \mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(x)$ and all $x>0$, in which $\left\{\mathrm{X}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is given by (2.8).
Proof. See Subsection 5.3.
The next theorem is the main result of the paper. It verifies that the function $v(x)$ given by Corollary 3.2 coincides with both the value function $\widetilde{\mathrm{V}}(x)$ of the concavified problem (3.1) and the value function $\mathrm{V}(x)$ of the original problem (2.9). It also states that the functions $\pi^{*}(x)$ and $c^{*}(x)$, respectively given by (3.4) and (3.11), provide feedback optimal controls for both the concavified and the original problems.

Theorem 3.2. Let $x_{0}$ and $v(x)$ be given by (3.28), and $\varphi(y)$ and $\psi(y)$ be as in Theorem 3.1. Define also the feedback functions

$$
c^{*}(x)= \begin{cases}0, & 0<x<x_{0} \\ \alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\varphi\left(v^{\prime}(x)\right)\right), & x \geq x_{0}\end{cases}
$$

and

$$
\pi^{*}(x)= \begin{cases}\frac{\mu(1-\lambda)}{\sigma^{2}} x, & 0<x<x_{0} \\ \frac{\mu}{\sigma^{2} \rho}(1+\rho x) \psi\left(v^{\prime}(x)\right), & x \geq x_{0}\end{cases}
$$

It then holds that $\mathrm{V}(x)=\widetilde{\mathrm{V}}(x)=v(x)$ for all $x>0$, in which $\mathrm{V}(x)$ and $\widetilde{\mathrm{V}}(x)$ are value functions of problems (2.9) and (3.1), respectively. Furthermore, for any $x>0$, the SDE

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\mathrm{dX}_{t}^{*}=\left((r+\rho) \mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}+\mu \pi^{*}\left(\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right)-\left(1+\rho \mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right) c^{*}\left(\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t+\sigma \pi^{*}\left(\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right) \mathrm{dB}_{t} \\
\mathrm{X}_{0}^{*}=x
\end{array}\right.
$$

admits a unique strong solution $\left\{\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$, and $\left\{\left(\pi^{*}\left(\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right), c^{*}\left(\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right)\right)\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is a common optimal feedback control pair for both problems (2.9) and (3.1).

Before providing the proof, let us briefly discuss the optimal policies given by (3.31) and (3.30). The agent optimal investment and consumption depends on whether she should take austerity measures or not. At time $t \geq 0$, let $\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*}$ be her (optimally controlled) current wealth and $\mathrm{H}_{t}^{*}$ be her current consumption habit corresponding to her past optimally controlled consumption process $\left\{\mathrm{C}_{s}^{*}\right\}_{0 \leq s<t}$. Then,

- If her wealth-to-habit ratio $\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}=\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*} / \mathrm{H}_{t}^{*}$ is below the austerity threshold $x_{0}$, she will take austerity measures by not consuming (i.e. $\mathrm{C}_{t}^{*}=c=0$ by (2.7) and (3.30)) and investing a fixed proportion $\mu(1-\lambda) / \sigma^{2}$ of her wealth in the risky asset (since $\Pi_{t}^{*} / \mathrm{W}_{t}^{*}=\pi^{*}\left(\mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}\right) / \mathrm{X}_{t}^{*}=\mu(1-\lambda) / \sigma^{2}$ according to (2.7) and (3.31)). In particular, the agent takes this austerity measure since she is loss averse when her consumption rate is in the range $\left(0, \alpha \mathrm{H}_{t}^{*}\right)$. For low levels of wealth (determined precisely by the condition $\left.0<\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*} \leq x_{0} \mathrm{H}^{*} t\right)$, the agent prefers to avoid consumption and built up wealth rather than consuming at a rate in the range $\left(0, \alpha \mathrm{H}_{t}^{*}\right)$.

Furthermore, our numerical investigation in the next section indicates that the agent adjust her consumption and investment behavior to a more moderate regime as the wealth-to-habit ratio increases. In particular, the portfolio weight of the risky asset and the ratio of the net consumption rate to wealth are both adjust from higher to lower levels as wealth-to-habit ratio increases. See the bottom two plots of Figure 2 in the next section.

In summary, the agent's optimal policy is to invest a fixed portion of her wealth and consume nothing in the austerity region (i.e. $\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*}<x_{0} \mathrm{H}_{t}^{*}$ ). In the prosperity region (i.e. $\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*} \geq x_{0} \mathrm{H}_{t}^{*}$ ), the agent consumes above her habit reference point and invest less aggressively in the stock. As the ratio of wealth to habit increases, the agent consumes and invests more moderately, in that the portfolio rate of the stock and the consumption-to-wealth ratio are smaller compare to their levels near the austerity region.

The goal of this subsection is to reproduce numerical experiments in other papers using our model. Doing so serves two purposes. Firstly, it provides an alternative way of validating our results. We provide connection between our model and three other infinite horizon optimal consumption and investment models, namely,
(a) The classical infinite horizon model in [Mer69] under a power utility.
(b) The multiplicative habit formation model with (strictly concave) power utility in [Rog13].
(c) The optimal policies in [ABY22] under habit formation constraint.

These models are limiting cases of our model, in that they are obtained by letting specific parameters approach certain values in our model.

We start with the classical infinite horizon optimal investment and consumption problem in [Mer69], namely,

$$
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{M}}(w)=\sup _{(\Pi, \mathrm{C}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0}(w)} \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{+\infty} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta t} \frac{\mathrm{C}_{t}^{p}}{p} \mathrm{~d} t\right], \quad w>0
$$

In this model, the value function is

$$
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{M}}(w)=\gamma_{\mathrm{M}}^{p} \cdot \frac{w^{p}}{p}, \quad w>0
$$

and the feedback optimal policies are $\left\{\Pi_{\mathrm{M}}\left(\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*}\right)\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ and $\left\{\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{M}}\left(\mathrm{W}_{t}^{*}\right)\right\}_{t \geq 0}$, in which

$$
\Pi_{\mathrm{M}}(w):=\frac{\mu}{(1-p) \sigma^{2}} w, \quad \text { and } \quad \mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{M}}(w):=\gamma_{\mathrm{M}} w
$$

with the constant $\gamma_{\mathrm{M}}$ given by

$$
\gamma_{\mathrm{M}}:=\frac{1}{1-p}\left[\delta-p\left(r+\frac{\mu^{2}}{2(1-p) \sigma^{2}}\right)\right]

Consider our model with the power S-shaped utility (4.1). As $\alpha, \epsilon_{1} \rightarrow 0^{+}$for the utility function $\mathrm{U}(c)$ in (4.1), the function $\mathrm{U}(c)+\epsilon_{1}^{p} / p$ becomes the power utility function in (4.4). It then follows that for small values of $\rho, \alpha$, and $\epsilon_{1}$, the optimal stock proportion $\pi^{*}(x) / x$ and the optimal proportional consumption $c^{*}(x) / x$ in our model should approach, respectively, the constants $\frac{\mu}{(1-p) \sigma^{2}}$ and $\gamma_{\mathrm{M}}$ in Merton's model. # 4.5 Non-power S-shaped utilities 

Our previous examples mainly focus on the commonly used power S-shaped utility functions and illustrate some optimal portfolio and consumption behavior induced by the loss-aversion and the habit formation. However, our theoretical characterization of the optimal relative policies and the associated free boundary problems in Theorem 3.2 are applicable to general S-shaped utilities as long as Assumptions 3.1 and 3.2 are satisfied. For instance, we may consider the following two examples of non-power S-shaped utility functions that appeared in the literature:
(i) The Exponential S-shaped utility, for $q \geq p>0, \kappa \geq 1$,

$$
\mathrm{U}(c)= \begin{cases}1-\mathrm{e}^{-p(c-\alpha)}, & c>\alpha \\ \kappa\left(\mathrm{e}^{-q(c-\alpha)}-1\right), & 0 \leq c \leq \alpha\end{cases}
$$

(ii) The Symmetric Asymptotic Hyperbolic Absolute Risk Aversion (SAHARA) S-shaped utility

$$
\mathrm{U}(c)= \begin{cases}\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\gamma_{1}, \beta_{1}}(c-\alpha), & c>\alpha \\ -\mathrm{U}_{-}^{\gamma_{2}, \beta_{2}}(\alpha-c), & 0 \leq c \leq \alpha\end{cases}
$$

where the utility function $\mathrm{U}^{\gamma, \beta}(x)$, introduced by [CPV11], is given by

$$
\mathrm{U}^{\gamma, \beta}(x):= \begin{cases}\frac{1}{1-\gamma^{2}}\left(x+\gamma \sqrt{x^{2}+\beta^{2}}\right)\left(x+\sqrt{x^{2}+\beta^{2}}\right)^{-\gamma}, & \gamma>0, \gamma \neq 1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \log \left(x+\sqrt{x^{2}+\beta^{2}}\right)+\frac{x}{2\left(x+\sqrt{x^{2}+\beta^{2}}\right)}, & \gamma=1\end{cases}
$$

for $x \in \mathbb{R}$, in which $\gamma>0$ is the risk-aversion parameter and $\beta>0$ is the scaling factor. They are characterized by their absolute risk-aversion function $-\left(\mathrm{U}^{\gamma, \beta}\right)^{\prime \prime}(x) /\left(\mathrm{U}^{\gamma, \beta}\right)^{\prime}(x)=\gamma / \sqrt{x^{2}+\beta^{2}}, x>0$. ### 5.1 Solution to an auxiliary boundary value problem

As a preparation for the proof of Theorem 3.1, this subsection first investigates an auxiliary system of ODEs with certain boundary value conditions. In particular, let us consider the boundary value problem

$$
\begin{cases}\varphi^{\prime}(y)=g_{1}(y, \varphi(y), \psi(y)), & y<\bar{y} \\ \psi^{\prime}(y)=g_{2}(y, \varphi(y), \psi(y)), & y<\bar{y} \\ \varphi(\bar{y})=\phi_{0}, & \psi(\bar{y})=\Psi(\bar{y})\end{cases}
$$

for a given boundary $\bar{y} \in\left(\gamma \phi_{0}, \phi_{0}\right)$.
Throughout this subsection, we adopt the notations and assumptions in Theorem 3.1. Let us define $\gamma:=$ $\frac{\lambda}{\lambda \cdot 1} \in(0,1)$,

$$
\mathcal{D}:=\{(y, \varphi, \psi): y>0, \varphi>0, \psi \in(0,1)\}
$$

and

$$
\Psi(y):=\frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\phi_{0} \mu^{2}}\left(\frac{\delta}{\lambda}+r+\rho-\delta\right)\left(y-\phi_{0}\right)=\frac{1}{\phi_{0}}(\lambda-1)\left(y-\phi_{0}\right), \quad y>0
$$

To derive the second equation in (5.3), we have used the fact that $\lambda$ satisfies

$$
\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} \lambda^{2}-\left(\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}}+r+\rho-\delta\right) \lambda-\delta=0
$$

as pointed out in Remark 3.4. Note also that $\Psi\left(\gamma \phi_{0}\right)=1, \Psi\left(\phi_{0}\right)=0$. Finally, for $(y, \varphi, \psi) \in \mathcal{D}$, we define

$$
g_{1}(y, \varphi, \psi):=\frac{\varphi}{y}(1-\psi)
$$

and

$$
g_{2}(y, \varphi, \psi):=-\frac{2 \rho \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left[\frac{1-\psi}{y}\left(\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \psi-\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(\varphi)+\frac{r-\delta}{\rho}+1-\alpha\right)-\frac{r+\rho}{\rho \varphi}+\frac{\delta}{\rho y}\right]
$$

Because the boundary value conditions in (5.1) are in the interior of $\mathcal{D}$, and $g_{1}$ and $g_{2}$ are locally Lipschitz inside $\mathcal{D}$, (5.1) is locally solvable inside $\mathcal{D}$. In particular, there exists a function $\epsilon:\left(\gamma \phi_{0}, \phi_{0}\right) \rightarrow[0, \infty)$ with $\epsilon(y)<y$, such that $\left(\epsilon(\bar{y}), \bar{y}\right]$ is the maximal interval in which the solution of (5.1) exists inside $\mathcal{D}$.

The next result provides further properties of the solution of (5.1) and, specifically, its dependence on $\bar{y}$. Figure 9 illustrates the solutions of (5.1) for various values of $\bar{y}$, and it is helpful to refer to this figure when reading the statement of the lemma and its proof.

Lemma 5.1. Given a $\bar{y} \in\left(\gamma \phi_{0}, \phi_{0}\right)$, let $\left(\varphi_{\bar{y}}(\cdot), \psi_{\bar{y}}(\cdot)\right)$ be the local solution of (5.1) and $\epsilon(\bar{y})$ be the left endpoint of its maximal existence interval. Then, we have:
(i) If $\gamma \phi_{0}<\bar{y}^{\prime}<\bar{y}<\phi_{0}$ and $\epsilon(\bar{y})<\bar{y}^{\prime}$, then $\varphi_{\bar{y}^{\prime}}(y)>\varphi_{\bar{y}}(y)$ and $\psi_{\bar{y}^{\prime}}(y)>\psi_{\bar{y}}(y)$ for values of $y$ at which both solutions exist (i.e. for $\max \left\{\epsilon(\bar{y}), \epsilon\left(\bar{y}^{\prime}\right)\right\}<y \leq \bar{y}^{\prime}$ ).
(ii) If $\epsilon(\bar{y})>0$, then $\left\{\left(y, \varphi_{\bar{y}}(y), \psi_{\bar{y}}(y)\right): \epsilon(\bar{y})<y \leq \bar{y}\right\}$ exits $\mathcal{D}$ either through $\overline{\mathcal{D}}_{0}:=\left(0, \phi_{0}\right)^{2} \times\{0\}$, or through $\overline{\mathcal{D}}_{1}:=\left(0, \gamma \phi_{0}\right) \times\left(0, \phi_{0}\right) \times\{1\}$.
(iii) For $\bar{y}$ sufficiently close to $\gamma \phi_{0}$ (respectively, $\phi_{0}$ ), $\left\{\left(y, \varphi_{\bar{y}}(y), \psi_{\bar{y}}(y)\right): \epsilon(\bar{y})<y \leq \bar{y}\right\}$ exits $\mathcal{D}$ through $\overline{\mathcal{D}}_{1}$ (respectively, through $\overline{\mathcal{D}}_{0}$ ).

Proof. (i) Define $(\bar{\varphi}(y), \bar{\psi}(y)):=\left(\phi_{0}, \Psi(y)\right), y \in(0, \bar{y})$, with $\Psi(\cdot)$ given by (5.3). For $y \in(0, \bar{y})$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \bar{\psi}^{\prime}(y)-g_{2}(y, \bar{\varphi}(y), \bar{\psi}(y)) \\
& =\Psi^{\prime}(y)+\frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left[\frac{1-\Psi(y)}{y}\left(\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} \Psi(y)-\rho \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}\left(\phi_{0}\right)+r-\delta+\rho-\rho \alpha\right)-\frac{r+\delta}{\phi_{0}}+\frac{\delta}{y}\right] \\
& =\frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left[\left(\frac{\delta}{\lambda}-\delta\right) \frac{1}{\phi_{0}}+\frac{\delta}{y}+\frac{1-\Psi(y)}{y}\left(-\rho \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}\left(\phi_{0}\right)-\rho \alpha+y \Psi^{\prime}(y)-\frac{\delta}{\lambda}\right)\right] \\
& \leq \frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left[\delta\left(\frac{1}{y}-\frac{1}{\phi_{0}}\right)\left(1-\frac{1}{\lambda}\right)+\frac{\Psi(y) \delta}{\lambda y}\right]=0
\end{aligned}
$$

We have used $\Psi^{\prime}(y)=\frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\phi_{0} \mu^{2}}\left(\frac{\delta}{\lambda}+r+\rho-\delta\right)$ and $\Psi(y)=y \Psi^{\prime}(y)-\frac{2 \sigma^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\left(\frac{\delta}{\lambda}+r+\rho-\delta\right)$ (c.f. (5.3)) for the second step. The third step follows from $-\rho \mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}\left(\phi_{0}\right)-\rho \alpha+y \Psi^{\prime}(y)=-\rho c_{0}+\frac{y}{\phi_{0}}(\lambda-1)<0$, in which we have used $\phi_{0}:=\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\left(c_{0}-\alpha\right)$ from Lemma 3.1 and that $\lambda<0$ by (3.20). The last equality directly follows from (5.3). By (5.4), we also have that $\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}(y)-g_{1}(y, \bar{\varphi}(y), \bar{\psi}(y))=-\frac{1}{y} \bar{\varphi}(y)(1-\bar{\psi}(y)) \leq 0$. We have thus shown that

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\bar{\varphi}^{\prime}(y) \leq g_{1}(y, \bar{\varphi}(y), \bar{\psi}(y)) \\
\bar{\psi}^{\prime}(y) \leq g_{2}(y, \bar{\varphi}(y), \bar{\psi}(y))
\end{array}\right.
$$

for $y \in(0, \bar{y})$. Since $\bar{\varphi}(\cdot)$ and $\bar{\psi}(\cdot)$ (trivially) satisfy the terminal conditions of (5.1), the comparison theorem for the system of differential equation in (5.1) (see Lemma B. 2 of [ABY22]) then yields that $\psi_{\bar{y}}(y) \leq \Psi(y)$ for $y \in\left(\epsilon(\bar{y}), \bar{y}\right)$. Therefore, $\psi_{\bar{y}^{\prime}}\left(\bar{y}^{\prime}\right)=\Psi\left(\bar{y}^{\prime}\right) \geq \psi_{\bar{y}}\left(\bar{y}^{\prime}\right)$. Statement (i) then follows by comparing (e.g., using Lemma B. 2 of [ABY22]) $\left(\phi_{\bar{y}^{\prime}}, \psi_{\bar{y}^{\prime}}\right)$ and $\left(\phi_{\bar{y}}, \psi_{\bar{y}}\right)$ over the domain $\left(\max \left\{\epsilon(\bar{y}), \epsilon\left(\bar{y}^{\prime}\right)\right\}, \bar{y}^{\prime}\right]$. That the inequalities are strict follows from uniqueness of the solution of (5.1).
