From the definition of $z_{n}^{*}$ in (5.12) and the continuity of $\widetilde{\psi}(z)$, we also conclude that $\widetilde{\psi}^{\prime}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)=0$ for all $n \geq 1$.

We next claim that $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)=1$. As $\widetilde{\psi}^{\prime}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)=0$ for all $n \geq 1$, the second equation in (5.11) yields

$$
\widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)^{2}+b_{n} \widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)+c_{n}=0, \quad n \geq 1
$$

in which $b_{n}:=\kappa[r-\delta+\rho(1-\alpha)]-1-\kappa \rho \mathrm{U}_{+}^{(l-1)}\left(\widetilde{\varphi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)\right)$ and $c_{n}:=\kappa \rho \mathrm{U}_{+}^{(l-1)}\left(\widetilde{\varphi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)\right)-\kappa[r+\rho(1-\alpha)]+\kappa \frac{(r+\rho) e^{z_{n}^{*}}}{\widetilde{\varphi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)}$. Thanks to the fact that $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty}\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\widetilde{\varphi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)\right)=\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(\widetilde{\varphi}(-\infty))=\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left(\varphi\left(0^{+}\right)\right)=+\infty$, we have $b_{n} \rightarrow-\infty$ and $c_{n} \rightarrow+\infty$. Moreover, $b_{n} / c_{n} \rightarrow-1$ as $n \rightarrow \infty$. Therefore, if follows from (5.13) that

$$
\widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right) \geq \frac{-b_{n}-\sqrt{b_{n}^{2}-4 c_{n}}}{2}=\frac{2 c_{n}}{-b_{n}+\sqrt{b_{n}^{2}-4 c_{n}}}=\frac{2}{\frac{b_{n}}{c_{n}}+\sqrt{\left(\frac{b_{n}}{c_{n}}\right)^{2}-\frac{4}{c_{n}}}} \rightarrow 1
$$

as $n \rightarrow \infty$. As $\widetilde{\psi}(z) \leq 1$ for all $z \in\left(-\infty, z_{0}\right]$, we must have $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)=1$, as claimed.
Finally, by the definition of $z_{n}^{*}$ in (5.12), we have $\widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}\right) \geq \widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)$ for all $n \geq 1$. Therefore, $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}\right) \geq$ $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \widetilde{\psi}\left(z_{n}^{*}\right)=1$. Because $\left\{z_{n}\right\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ was arbitrarily chosen, we conclude that $\liminf _{z \rightarrow-\infty} \widetilde{\psi}(z) \geq 1$. As it has been argued that $\lim \sup _{z \rightarrow-\infty} \widetilde{\psi}(z) \leq 1$ in view of $\widetilde{\psi}(z) \leq 1$ for $z \leq z_{0}$. We have thus shown that $\lim _{z \rightarrow-\infty} \widetilde{\psi}(z)=1$ in Case 2, which completes the proof of Theorem 3.1.(i).
Proof of Theorem 3.1.(ii). By (3.10), we have $\mathrm{G}^{\prime}(\phi)=-\alpha-\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}(\phi)$. Differentiating (3.25) with respect to $y$ then yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
u^{\prime}(y)= & \frac{1}{\delta}\left[\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}}\left(\varphi^{\prime}(y) \psi(y)+\varphi(y) \psi^{\prime}(y)\right)-\varphi^{\prime}(y)\left(\alpha+\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}(\varphi(y))\right)+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}\left(1-\varphi^{\prime}(y)\right)\right] \\
= & \frac{1}{\delta}\left[-\frac{\varphi(y)(1-\psi(y))}{y}\left(\frac{r-\delta+\rho}{\rho}-\alpha-\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}(\varphi(y))\right)+\frac{r+\rho}{\rho}-\frac{\delta \varphi(y)}{\rho y}\right] \\
& +\frac{1}{\delta}\left[-\varphi^{\prime}(y)\left(\alpha+\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime(-1)}(\varphi(y))\right)+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}-\varphi^{\prime}(y) \frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}\right]=\frac{y-\varphi(y)}{\rho y}
\end{aligned}
$$

which is (3.26). Setting $y=y_{0}$ yields $u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)=\left(y_{0}-\varphi\left(y_{0}\right)\right) /\left(\rho y_{0}\right)$. As $\varphi\left(y_{0}\right)=\phi_{0}$ by (3.24), we obtain the first boundary condition in (3.22). The second boundary condition follows from (3.25),

$$
u\left(y_{0}\right)=\frac{1}{\delta}\left[\left(\frac{\delta}{\rho \lambda}+\frac{r+\rho-\delta}{\rho}\right)\left(y_{0}-\phi_{0}\right)+\mathrm{G}\left(\phi_{0}\right)+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}\left(y_{0}-\phi_{0}\right)\right]=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho \lambda}+\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta}
$$

in which we used $\mathrm{G}\left(\phi_{0}\right)=\mathrm{U}(0)$ that was shown in (3.12).
To show that the differential equation in (3.24) also holds, we proceed as follows. Differentiating (5.14) with respect to $y$ and noting that $\varphi^{\prime}(y)=\frac{1}{y} \varphi(y)(1-\psi(y))$ (by (3.23)) yield

$$
u^{\prime \prime}(y)=\frac{1}{\rho y^{2}} \varphi(y) \psi(y), \quad 0<y<y_{0}
$$

which is (3.27). Therefore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}} y^{2} u^{\prime \prime}(y)+\mathrm{G}\left(y-\rho y u^{\prime}(y)\right)+(\delta-r-\rho) y u^{\prime}(y)-\delta u(y) \\
& =\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \varphi(y) \psi(y)+\mathrm{G}(\varphi(y))+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}(y-\varphi(y))-\delta u(y)=0
\end{aligned}
$$

in which the last step follows from (3.25).

To show that $u$ is convex, we use (5.15) to obtain $u^{\prime \prime} \geq 0$ because of $\varphi, \psi \geq 0$. Furthermore, in view that $u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho y_{0}}<0$ by (5.14), and that $u^{\prime \prime}<0$, we conclude that $u^{\prime}(y)<0$ for $y \in\left(0, y_{0}\right)$. Thus, $u$ is decreasing.

It only remains to show that $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} u^{\prime}(y)=-\infty$. In Theorem 3.1.(i), we have shown that either $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \varphi(y)>0$ or $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \psi(y)>0$ (or both). If $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \varphi(y)>0$, we have $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \frac{\varphi(y)}{y}=+\infty$. We thus deduce from (5.14) that $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} u^{\prime}(y)=\frac{1}{\rho}-\frac{1}{\rho} \lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \frac{\varphi(y)}{y}=-\infty$. If $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} \psi(y)=1$, we assume $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0+} u^{\prime}(y)=-\infty$ does not hold and argue by contradiction. Because $u^{\prime}$ is increasing and $u^{\prime}\left(y_{0}\right)=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho y_{0}}<0$ by (5.14), there exists a constant $m>0$ such that $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} u^{\prime}(y)=-m$. It then follows from (5.14) that

$$
\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \frac{\varphi(y)}{y}=1+\rho m \in(1,+\infty)
$$

which yields $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \varphi(y)=0$. By L'Hôpital's rule, (3.23), and the fact $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \psi(y)=1$ from part $(i)$, we then obtain

$$
\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \frac{\varphi(y)}{y}=\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \varphi^{\prime}(y)=\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \frac{\varphi(y)}{y}(1-\psi(y))=0
$$

which yields a contradiction. Thus, we must have $\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} u^{\prime}(y)=-\infty$ as claimed.

# 5.3 Proof of Lemma 3.2 

We first show that $v(x)$ is lower bounded. By (3.21) and (3.28), we have

$$
v(x)=\frac{y_{0}-\phi_{0}}{\rho \lambda}\left(\frac{x}{x_{0}}\right)^{\frac{\lambda}{\lambda-1}}+\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta}, \quad x \in\left(0, x_{0}\right)
$$

As $v(x)$ is strictly increasing (by Corollary 3.2), we deduce that

$$
v(x)>v(0)=\frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta} \in \mathbb{R}, \quad x>0
$$

Let $\left(\varphi(y), \psi(y), y_{0}\right)$ be the solution of the system of problems (3.23) and (3.24) in Theorem 3.1, and let $u(y)$ be the solution of (3.16)-(3.18) (given in Corollary 3.1). In light of the item (i) of Theorem 3.1, we shall split the proof into two separate cases, depending on whether $\varphi(0)>0$ or $\psi(0)=1$.

Case 1: Assume that $\varphi(0)>0$. In this case, we will show that $|v(x)|$ is in fact uniformly bounded for $x>0$, which readily yields (3.29). Let $\left(u(y), y_{0}\right)$ be the solution of (3.16)-(3.18) in Corollary 3.1. It was shown in the proof of Corollary 3.2 that $\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x) \in\left(0, y_{0}\right)$ for $x>x_{0}$. Using (3.28) and then applying the change-of-variable $y=\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x) \Leftrightarrow x=-u^{\prime}(y)$, we obtain that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lim _{x \rightarrow+\infty} v(x)=\lim _{x \rightarrow+\infty}\left[u\left(\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x)\right)+x\left(u^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(-x)\right]=\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}}\left[u(y)-u^{\prime}(y) y\right] \\
& =\frac{1}{\delta} \lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}}\left[\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \varphi(y) \psi(y)+\mathrm{G}(\varphi(y))+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}(y-\varphi(y))\right]-\lim _{y \rightarrow 0^{+}} \frac{y-\varphi(y)}{\rho} \\
& =\frac{1}{\delta}\left[\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \varphi(0) \psi(0)+\mathrm{G}(\varphi(0))-\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho} \varphi(0)\right]+\frac{\varphi(0)}{\rho}<+\infty
\end{aligned}
$$

The third equality follows from (3.25) and (3.26). The last step follows from the boundedness of $\varphi(y)$ and $\psi(y)$ (see Theorem 3.1.(i)) and that, by (3.10) and $\varphi(0)>0$, we have

$$
\mathrm{G}(\varphi(0)):=\mathrm{K}+\mathrm{U}_{+}\left(\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(\varphi(0))\right)-\varphi(0)\left(\alpha+\left(\mathrm{U}_{+}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}(\varphi(0))\right)<+\infty
$$

Combing (5.16), (5.17), and the fact that $v(x)$ is increasing (by Corollary 3.2), we conclude that $|v(x)|$ is uniformly bounded for $x>0$, and (3.29) easily follows.

Case 2: Assume that $\psi(0)=1$. Take an arbitrary $x>0$ and any admissible $\left(\pi_{t}, c_{t}\right)_{t \geq 0} \in \mathcal{A}_{\text {rel. }}(x)$. Consider the process $\left\{\mathrm{Y}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ given by

$$
\mathrm{Y}_{t}:=\exp \left(-\frac{\mu}{\sigma} \mathrm{B}_{t}-\left[r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right] t+\rho \int_{0}^{t} c_{s} \mathrm{~d} s\right), \quad t \geq 0
$$

Note that $\left\{\mathrm{Y}_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 0}$ is the unique (strong) solution of the stochastic differential equation

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathrm{Y}_{t}}{\mathrm{~V}_{t}}=-\left(r+\rho\left(1-c_{t}\right)\right) \mathrm{d} t-\frac{\mu}{\sigma} \mathrm{dB}_{t}, \quad t \geq 0 \\
\mathrm{Y}_{0}=1
\end{array}\right.
$$

From (2.8) and (5.19), it is easy to see that $\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}+\int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}} c_{s} \mathrm{Y}_{s} \mathrm{~d} s=x+\int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}}\left(\sigma \pi_{s}-\frac{\mu}{\sigma} \mathrm{X}_{s}\right) \mathrm{Y}_{s} \mathrm{~d} \mathrm{~B}_{s}, \mathrm{~T} \geq 0$. Therefore, by some standard localizing arguments, it holds that $\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right] \leq x$ for $\mathrm{T}>0$. Using (3.14) then yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{E}\left[v\left(\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right] & =\mathrm{E}\left[v\left(\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)-\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}+\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right] \leq \mathrm{E}\left[u\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)+\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}} \mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right] \\
& \leq \mathrm{E}\left[u\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right]+x, \quad \mathrm{~T}>0
\end{aligned}
$$

By taking (5.16) into account, it follows that

$$
e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} \frac{\mathrm{U}(0)}{\delta} \leq \mathrm{E}\left[e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} v\left(\mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right] \leq \mathrm{E}\left[e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} u\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right]+x e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}, \quad \mathrm{~T}>0
$$

That is, to prove the transversality condition (3.29), it is sufficient to show that

$$
\lim _{\mathrm{T} \rightarrow+\infty} \mathrm{E}\left[e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} u\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right]=0
$$

To this end, we first note that, by (3.25),

$$
\begin{aligned}
u(y) & =\frac{1}{\delta}\left[\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \rho \sigma^{2}} \varphi(y) \psi(y)+\mathrm{G}(\varphi(y))+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\rho}(y-\varphi(y))\right] \\
& \leq \frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \delta \rho \sigma^{2}} \phi_{0}+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\delta \rho} y_{0}+\frac{1}{\delta} \mathrm{G}(\varphi(y))
\end{aligned}
$$

for $0<y<y_{0}$. Furthermore, by Assumption 3.2, there exists constants $\mathrm{A}_{1}, \mathrm{~A}_{2}>0$ and $\mathrm{A}_{3} \geq 0$ such that

$$
\mathrm{G}(\varphi(y)) \leq \mathrm{A}_{1}+\mathrm{A}_{2} \varphi(y)^{-\mathrm{A}_{3}}, \quad y \in\left(0, y_{0}\right]
$$

Next, take an arbitrary constant $\epsilon>0$. From (5.21), (5.22), and Lemma 5.2 below, it follows that,

$$
\begin{aligned}
u(y) & \leq \frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \delta \rho \sigma^{2}} \phi_{0}+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\delta \rho} y_{0}+\frac{1}{\delta} \mathrm{G}(\varphi(y)) \\
& \leq \frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \delta \rho \sigma^{2}} \phi_{0}+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\delta \rho} y_{0}+\frac{\mathrm{A}_{1}}{\delta}+\frac{\mathrm{A}_{2}}{\delta} \varphi(y)^{-\mathrm{A}_{3}} \\
& \leq \frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \delta \rho \sigma^{2}} \phi_{0}+\frac{\delta-r-\rho}{\delta \rho} y_{0}+\frac{\mathrm{A}_{1}}{\delta}+\frac{\mathrm{A}_{2} \mathrm{~B}_{\epsilon}^{-\mathrm{A}_{3}}}{\delta} y^{-\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3}}
\end{aligned}
$$

for $y \in\left(0, y_{0}\right)$, in which $\mathrm{B}_{\epsilon}>0$ is a constant that may depend on $\epsilon$ (see Lemma 5.2 as below). By choosing appropriate constants $\widetilde{\mathrm{A}}$ and $\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon}>0$, we may rewrite (5.23) in a way that

$$
u(y) \leq \widetilde{\mathrm{A}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} y^{-\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3}}, \quad 0<y \leq y_{0}
$$

By virtue of (5.18) and (5.24), we derive that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{E}\left[e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} u\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right] \leq \widetilde{\mathrm{A}} e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} \mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{e}^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)^{-\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3}}\right] \\
& =\widetilde{\mathrm{A}} e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} \mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{e}^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} \exp \left(-\frac{\mu}{\sigma} \mathrm{~B}_{\mathrm{T}}-\left[r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right] \mathrm{T}+\rho \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}} c_{s} \mathrm{~d} s\right)^{-\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3}}\right] \\
& =\widetilde{\mathrm{A}} e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} \mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{e}^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} \exp \left(\epsilon \mathrm{~A}_{3} \frac{\mu}{\sigma} \mathrm{~B}_{\mathrm{T}}+\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3}\left[r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right] \mathrm{T}-\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3} \rho \int_{0}^{\mathrm{T}} c_{s} \mathrm{~d} s\right)\right] \\
& \leq \widetilde{\mathrm{A}} e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} \exp \left(\left[\epsilon \mathrm{~A}_{3}\left(r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)-\delta\right] \mathrm{T}\right) \mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{e}^{\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3} \frac{\mu}{\sigma} \mathrm{~B}_{\mathrm{T}}}\right] \\
& \leq \widetilde{\mathrm{A}} e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} \exp \left(\left[\epsilon \mathrm{~A}_{3}\left(r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)+\epsilon^{2} \mathrm{~A}_{3}^{2} \frac{\mu^{2}}{\sigma^{2}}-\delta\right] \mathrm{T}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

On the other hand, by the Legendre transform and (5.16), it holds that $u(y) \geq \lim _{x \rightarrow 0^{+}}(v(x)-x y)=v(0)$ for all $y>0$. It thus follows that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} v(0) \leq \mathrm{E}\left[e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}} u\left(\mathrm{Y}_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right] \\
& \leq \widetilde{\mathrm{A}} e^{-\delta \mathrm{T}}+\widetilde{\mathrm{B}}_{\epsilon} \exp \left(\left[\epsilon \mathrm{~A}_{3}\left(r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)+\epsilon^{2} \mathrm{~A}_{3}^{2} \frac{\mu^{2}}{\sigma^{2}}-\delta\right] \mathrm{T}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

for any $\epsilon>0$. Note that the value of the constant $\mathrm{A}_{3} \geq 0$ in (5.22) does not depend on $\epsilon$, we may choose a sufficiently small $\epsilon$ such that

$$
\epsilon \mathrm{A}_{3}\left(r+\rho+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)+\epsilon^{2} \mathrm{~A}_{3}^{2} \frac{\mu^{2}}{\sigma^{2}}<\delta
$$

By choosing such a value of $\epsilon$ in (5.25) and then letting $\mathrm{T} \rightarrow+\infty$, we obtain (5.20). This completes the proof.
To obtain (5.23) in the last part of the proof, we have used the next lemma.
Lemma 5.2. Assume that $\psi(0)=1$. Then, for any $\epsilon>0$, there exists a constant $\mathrm{B}_{\epsilon}>0$ such that $\varphi(y)>\mathrm{B}_{\epsilon} y^{\epsilon}$ for all $y \in\left(0, y_{0}\right]$.

Proof. Take an arbitrary $\epsilon>0$. As $\psi(0)=1$, there exists an $\eta \in\left(0, y_{0}\right)$ such that $1-\psi(y)<\epsilon$ for all $y \in(0, \eta)$. It then follows that

$$
\varphi^{\prime}(y)-\frac{\epsilon}{y} \varphi(y)<\varphi^{\prime}(y)-\frac{1-\psi(y)}{y} \varphi(y)=0, \quad y \in(0, \eta)
$$

in which the last step follows from (3.23). Let $f(y):=\varphi(\eta)(y / \eta)^{\epsilon}$ for $y \in(0, \eta)$. Note that $f(\eta)=\varphi(\eta)$ and

$$
\varphi^{\prime}(y)-\frac{\epsilon}{y} \varphi(y)<0=f^{\prime}(y)-\frac{\epsilon}{y} f(y), \quad y \in(0, \eta)
$$

we can apply the standard comparison theorem for boundary value ordinary differential equations (see, for instance, the Corollary on page 91 of [Wal98]) to obtain that

$$
\varphi(y)>f(y)=\frac{\varphi(\eta)}{\eta^{\epsilon}} y^{\epsilon} \geq \frac{\varphi(\eta)}{y_{0}^{\epsilon}} y^{\epsilon}, \quad 0<y<\eta
$$

As $\varphi(y)$ is increasing (according to Theorem 3.1.(i)), we also have

$$
\frac{\varphi(y)}{y^{\epsilon}}>\frac{\varphi(\eta)}{y_{0}^{\epsilon}}, \quad \eta \leq y \leq y_{0}
$$

Finally, by setting $\mathrm{B}_{\epsilon}:=\varphi(\eta) / y_{0}^{\epsilon}>0$, the last two inequalities lead to the desired result $\varphi(y) \geq \mathrm{B}_{\epsilon} y^{\epsilon}$ for all $0<y \leq y_{0}$.

abstract:
This paper studies a loss-averse version of the multiplicative habit
formation preference and the corresponding optimal investment and consumption
strategies over an infinite horizon. The agent's consumption preference is
depicted by a general S-shaped utility function of her consumption-to-habit
ratio. By considering the concave envelope of the S-shaped utility and the
associated dual value function, we provide a thorough analysis of the HJB
equation for the concavified problem via studying a related nonlinear free
boundary problem. Based on established properties of the solution to this free
boundary problem, we obtain the optimal consumption and investment policies in
feedback form. Some new and technical verification arguments are developed to
cope with generality of the utility function. The equivalence between the
original problem and the concavified problem readily follows from the structure
of the feedback controls. We also discuss some quantitative properties of the
optimal policies, complemented by illustrative numerical examples and their
financial implications.
